## 9. Scalability

ActionPilot is built using a stateless architecture designed to scale with user growth:

```
                            +-------------------+
                            |  Load Balancer    |
                            +-------------------+
                                      |
                 +--------------------+--------------------+
                 |                                         |
                 v                                         v
       +-------------------+                     +-------------------+
       | Express Server A  |                     | Express Server B  |
       | (Stateless API)   |                     | (Stateless API)   |
       +-------------------+                     +-------------------+
                 |                                         |
                 +--------------------+--------------------+
                                      |
                                      v
                             +-------------------+
                             |    Redis Cluster  |
                             |  (Queue / Cache)  |
                             +-------------------+
                                      |
                 +--------------------+--------------------+
                 |                                         |
                 v                                         v
       +-------------------+                     +-------------------+
       |   BullMQ Worker   |                     |   BullMQ Worker   |
       |   (Node Instance) |                     |   (Node Instance) |
       +-------------------+                     +-------------------+
```

### 9.1 Stateless API Nodes
The Express backend keeps no in-memory session states. Sessions are managed using JWTs, allowing API traffic to be distributed across multiple backend nodes behind a load balancer without configuration sync issues.

### 9.2 Asynchronous Job Queue (BullMQ & Redis)
High-latency tasks—such as AI analysis, risk calculations, standup generations, and push notification dispatches—are offloaded to the background queue. This keeps API response times fast. If background traffic spikes, additional worker instances can be scaled independently to process jobs from the Redis queue.

### 9.3 Database Optimization
PostgreSQL handles persistent state, and its load is optimized by indexing foreign keys and frequently queried status columns. Connection pooling is managed through the Prisma Client to prevent resource exhaustion during traffic spikes.

